Reorganization of the Middle East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Mazen, and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is the United States serious about the peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the US's Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, director of the planning staff at the US State Department, explains his "Roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq - and what the Iraqi people, with the help of the Americans, can now put on its feet - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented and peaceful Iraq could provide reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
It will, however, take some time to have any far-reaching changes in Iraq and across the entire Middle East.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the advance planning of the Americans and the whole world and thanks to the swift, concentrated and targeted intervention of the coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is smaller than assumed.
Here and there there is a need for humanitarian aid, but fortunately the announced major crisis never materialized.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced people within Iraq. The supply of food, water and medicine is generally sufficient or at least improving in most cases.
The US government has made available about $600 million through the United Nations and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian aid.
In addition, we must restore the basic order in Iraq.
Security is the indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, cannot return to work or to schools.
Following Saddam's downfall, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness and settling of scores.
Now it is the top priority to put an end to this violence.
In addition, it must be the task of international troops to secure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbours exacerbate the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures, so that they can look after their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more precisely as economic renewal.
Physical capital is in better condition than expected and the modern Iraq has a significant reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there is a lot of raw material to process in Iraq.
The US is providing more than $2 billion in support for the initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production will be raised to a higher level.
Long-term challenges include an increase in oil production and the reduction of Iraq's enormous debt.
The UN Security Council's decision to lift all sanctions is very welcome in this regard.
In the face of many religious, ethnic, geographical, and political fault lines in Iraqi society, helping to renew Iraq's politics is likely the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The Americans' goal - an intact Iraq where the law is respected and a democratic government is formed - is no castle in the air, especially not because Iraq has a well-educated population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue along the path it has taken and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are implemented.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported in order to utilize the enormous political potential for constructive decisions.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have an impact on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There's hardly a foreign policy issue that occupies and polarizes public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian issue.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU and the United Nations, the US developed a plan that brings us closer to this goal in stages.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent an important step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be persuaded to start this process and take measures to improve the situation, before tackling more far-reaching issues at the negotiating table.
It cannot be acceptable that terrorists ruin the peace process forever.
But a solution to the Palestinian problem is not automatically also a solution to all the problems of the Middle East.
Clear and evident are the challenges that Iran poses to us. This country is developing mass destruction weapons and supports terrorism.
Such behavior mocks the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues like this, there will be consequences.
If one were to refrain from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the U.S. would be ready to establish good relations with this country again.
Just as the US is prepared to intervene in Syria if substantial attitude changes are made there.
A rather general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
America too long tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to opt for a representative government form.
We have painfully felt that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the USA, the West, and the world at large.
That's why we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East, which was launched by US Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Even closed economic systems pose a danger.
As shown in the previous year's 'Arab Human Development Report' (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries), Arab countries in the Middle East lag far behind other regions in areas of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
For too long, these countries had to watch as the economic upswing passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If one were to realize the recently proposed plan for a free trade zone between the US and the Middle East within a decade, it would be a sustainable basis for such development.
